# Report Builder & Branding

## PDF Generation
- Primary engine: ReportLab (required); WeasyPrint (optional fallback)
- Two-pass build: Pass 1 captures page numbers via `PageMarker`, Pass 2 renders final PDF with dynamic TOC
- All sections are self-contained methods: `_create_<section>_section()`

## VAST Brand Compliance
- Primary color: VAST Blue RGB(0, 77, 153) → ReportLab (0.0, 0.3, 0.6)
- Headings: sans-serif (Helvetica), body: serif where appropriate
- Tables: alternating row colors for readability
- All reports must include VAST logo on title page
- Professional formatting: proper margins, page numbers, TOC with dot leaders

## Report Section Order (do not reorder without approval)
1. Title Page (cluster name, PSNT, date, organization)
2. Table of Contents (dynamic, auto-generated)
3. Executive Summary (cluster overview, hardware counts)
4. Cluster Information (version, features, config)
5. Hardware Summary (capacity metrics, storage)
6. Hardware Inventory (CBox/DBox tables with images)
7. Physical Rack Layout (42U rack diagrams)
8. Network Configuration (interfaces, VIPs, DNS, NTP)
9. Switch Port Mapping (when enabled)
10. Logical Network Diagram (topology visualization)
11. Logical Configuration (tenants, views, policies)
12. Security & Authentication

## Adding a New Section
1. Create `_create_<section>_section(story, data)` in `report_builder.py`
2. Add a `PageMarker("<section_key>")` flowable for TOC tracking
3. Register the section key in `_create_table_of_contents_dynamic()`
4. Follow existing patterns for table styling and error handling
5. Handle missing data gracefully — display "Data not available" rather than omitting

## Output Naming
- PDF: `vast_asbuilt_report_{cluster_name}_{YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS}.pdf`
- JSON: `vast_data_{cluster_name}_{YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS}.json`
